review.itemreviewed: Lightning Pro Double Dry 9.7mm Climbing Rope
review.reviewBody: I have only had this rope out on a few sport climbing trips and it is more frayed than an old climbing rope. I recently had to cut out 2 meters to get rid of a flat spot and some bad fraying. I checked all my metal gear to try and find a burr or something that would cause all the premature sheath wear but that just wasn't the case.  I feel safer on my 4 year old maxim rope than this thing.
review.name: Sheath frayed exceptionally fast

review.itemreviewed: Lightning Pro Double Dry 9.7mm Climbing Rope
review.reviewBody: I have climbed with this rope about 15 days and have a few initial impressions. This rope is supple, colorful, and easy to clip. Also, I love the 70 meter length (highly recommend for multi-pitch). For whatever reason, this rope knots up on me like crazy, no matter how I stack it - in or out of my rope bag. I can't help but think it is user error but my old 10.1 mm rope never did this and I haven't changed how I handle rope. Drives me crazy. It has also shown some wear a bit prematurely, nothing major but more than I would have expected. Overall, I think this rope will do the job for me, however, with how expensive it was I do kind of regret this decision and would go with a different rope in hindsight.
review.name: Was Hoping for More

review.itemreviewed: Lightning Pro Double Dry 9.7mm Climbing Rope
review.reviewBody: I couldn't decide between this rope and one from BD; so I bought both to compare side by side. This rope feels oh-so-sweet, and I imagine it would perform great at the crag.  The only problem is, I wanted the Bi-Flavin color and did not receive what I ordered.  Huge disappointment, since Backcountry is usually spot-on.  So I am going to try this rope again when they have the Bi-Flavin color in 70M back in stock.  In the meantime, FWIW:  This looks and feels like a very, very high quality rope, available to you at a nice sale price!
review.name: Nice Rope; Received Wrong Color

review.itemreviewed: Lightning Pro Double Dry 9.7mm Climbing Rope
review.reviewBody: This rope has been my go to for several years. It feels good inn the hands, is very pliable and flexible, and does not kink or twist. The bipattern is obviously awesome for rappels. Gives a very soft catch. It has also been very durable for a soft rope, and the dry treatment helps keep the dirt out. I don't lead hard routes on it anymore (simply due to it's age), but I still use it for mellow days out. Would buy again.
review.name: Quality rope

name: Lightning Pro Double Dry 9.7mm Climbing Rope

review.reviewBody: This is a great bag. Durable and comfortable, the build quality is really good which is important to me since I hate buying new bags all the time. This one will last. I also have a lot of shoulder and back issues and this bag is comfortable all day which is far from what I could say about my old bag. I also love the bottle holder. Mesh holders always stretch out and look trashy after a few months, but this design takes that problem away. I also like the tablet holder, I take that more than my laptop so it’s nice to have a dedicated slot for one.
review.name: Awesome Pack

review.reviewBody: I have lots of different packs, including several Camelbak packs.  I'm always in search of the "ideal" backpack for EDC, travel, etc.  I have/had lots and lots of packs.  Up until I purchased the Quantico, the Camelbak HAWG was probably my favorite, but it lacks a water bottle pocket, and dedicated laptop compartment.  I thought I'd try the Quantico and boy am I glad I did.  It's about the perfect size and weight for EDC and carry-on travel.  Has the perfect amount of internal and external organization and pockets.  It's not quite a beefy (thinner webbing straps, lighter zippers, and smaller buckles) as the other Camelbak military packs, but I have no reason to think this thing won't hold up for years of abuse.  It's also exceptionally comfortable!
review.name: Maybe the Perfect EDC Backpack

review.reviewBody: I bought this backpack a month ago and it has been very useful to me. I am happy with my purchase
review.name: Perfect backpack for me

review.reviewBody: I have had this bag for over 4 years now, I think i can comment on it.  The design is great, the partitioning of the pack is logical and nice.  When the weather turns foul, I have to wrap the bag in plastic so that my computer and other devices, let alone paperwork, don't get destroyed.  The material on the bottom of the bag needs be upgraded as mine is torn to shreds.  I like the bag, it met every requirement that i needed to use it for.  so long as it doesn't rain, I'm happy with it.
review.name: Great design, soggy mess when it rains

review.reviewBody:
I swear that this thing is a TARDIS as it holds so much. My main complaint is that I wish the zipper for the main compartment would close on the opposite side, rather than the side where the water bottle holder is. It's rather annoying to try and unzip the pack when you have a water bottle there, especially if you're using a larger bottle. More colors would be nice, though I'm happy with the grey color. A lower price would be very nice, though I think it's well worth it for the durability and space, especially in comparison with other backpacks/their costs on the market.
I will note that I have large breasts and I was not able to use the chest strap. This isn't a big deal to me, but I figure it's worth noting.
Also, my husband felt that the back was a little too flat for his liking.
review.name: TARDIS Backpack

review.reviewBody: I'm a student and ride a motorcycle. This pack provides all the room and then some for my books and other essential items I need. The side pocket is great for my morning coffee mug or an afternoon cold drink. Great products, never disappointed.
review.name: Durability / Quality

review.reviewBody: Had his bag over 2 years used it for school carrying a laptop and books and it is perfect. Holds everything I need and is made out of some pretty tough stuff. I also used it as my hunting and camping backpack just because I liked it so much even though it really isn't meant for it but it still did amazing. The only thing I wished it different was that you could add a spot for a water bladder. Im also in the Marine Corps and compared to my other bags that are given I prefer this bag.
review.name: Best Bag ever

review.reviewBody: I have a Dell Precision 7710 - and it won't fit in this pack.  Too small by about 3/8" - super bummed
review.name: I had to return :(

review.reviewBody: I really love the pack, it feels good on the back and well designed.Just big enough to carry all my daily stuff. The layout of the inside of the pack works well for organizing. Love the molle webbing and other sections on the backpack for attachments. There is one flaw that brought it down to 4 stars. The convenient open pouch on the back is good until you have to use the backpack in the rain. Pocket full of water!!! Since I have electronics in my backpack, the water starts to soak up in the material leaving the inside of the pack soggy. Thought about cutting my own drainage for the pouch but I don't want to ruin the integrity of the pack.
review.name: Awsome pack with one bad design flaw

review.reviewBody:
I have the black/camo colour which looks way better than the product photos — it looks as good in person as it does in the promo videos.
The soft fabrics in the electronics compartment, the bottom front cable compartment, and meticulously organised stationary section, and the lightweight straps really testify to the fact that this is an admin bag, not a bush basher. Any more than a long commute or short hike would introduce comfort issues due to the relatively narrow shoulder straps, lack of waist straps and missing lumbar support.
This pack is only suitable for a lite trek on a formed track, and anything more would require a different setup. That's not a complaint, because the Quantico not only looks good, but it does what it is designed for better than any other pack. It eliminates unnecessary bulk and cumbersome straps. It still however remains a very "rugged" solution for its purpose. I would ignore complaints about thin straps and weak points from reviewers who have chosen to compare the Quantico to something that it isn't.
Space wise, there should be enough space for a water bottle, pop-up umbrella (there is a small flat pocket on opposite side from water bottle pocket), laptop, iPad, stationary/cables/admin gear, sunnies, a very lite wind jacket, toiletries, change of underwear, spare shirt, and a few small misc items. The Quantico *could* be a very lite overnighter.
My main complaint is; the back padding makes my T-Shirt ride up my back when it's not tucked in — a minor but constant annoyance.
My favourite features are the colour (black camo), general aesthetic, fold out water bottle holder, and the great internal organisation (not underdone and not OTT).
review.name: Perfect Admin Carry

name: Quantico 23L Backpack

If I try to pull the hat down far enough to fill it out on top, it starts to cover my eyes. I was looking for a tight fit across the top, so this hat is not for me. review.itemreviewed: HY/RD Flat Mount Disc Brake Caliper
review.reviewBody:
I have been using Hy/Rd since I bought a 2013 cross bike with mechanical disc brakes. A few races later, I knew I wanted better. So I bought a set of Hy/Rd (that set was post-mount, not direct mount). They are maybe 80% of the way there to hydraulic all the way through, and anyway better than any bleed I can accomplish on my own with a whole-hydraulic setup. You may need that extra 20%. I descend confidently in and around Seattle on mine (two different sets on two different bikes).

This set is my third or fourth pair of them. Given the chance to build a road bike from scratch, I chose mechanical brake lines over these. And I am still happy.

Because happiness is the truth.
review.name: These brakes are the truth

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I like the bag overall, but the location of the straps that tighten the outside stretchy compartment are oddly placed. When they are buckled, they don’t let the zippered compartments open all the way. Other than that, I like it!
review.name: I like the bag overall,

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I can't complain that I received this as a replacement. I took it out yesterday on It's debut. These are my thoughts. This is more like laptop backpack as the back pocket is very narrow. The middle pocket is deep but can't be opened wider as the zipper stops halfway down on each side. I like to put my daily meals into the backpack but it being too narrow, I have to use a separate lunch bag.
There's not enough small pockets in the first pocket like my previous one. I'm on the fence on the outside pocket. The Only way to secure it is by using the clips/buckle on the side. It's hard to unclip the buckle while wearing it one shoulder to get into that front pocket. The side pocket for beverage works great!
Maybe day 2 outing will be better.
review.name: I can't complain that I

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I absolutely love my Nebula bag. It’s super durable and works for all my daily needs. It has so much space to fit everything I would need for day to day work or to go out and explore. The zippers are super smooth with no tugging on the fabric causing rips or tears. The size is perfect for me!
review.name: I absolutely love my Nebula

review.reviewBody: Great pack for school and work duties. Perfect fit and size for my motorcycle commute. Wish the back pack came with integrated reflectors or hi-viz panel for night riding on motorcycles or bikes. That would make this the absolute perfect backpack.
review.name: Great Pack

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I love everything about this pack except for one tiny detail. The clips from the mesh, stash pocket in the front need to be unclipped each time you want to unzip a compartment. I think the design would be improved if the stash pocket had different or no clips.
review.name: I love everything about this

review.reviewBody: I had the Nova and used it daily for 5 years. I thought it was perfect, but this is even better!  I have been using this pack daily for a few months and love that the front stash pocket can be tightened using the top cinch/stabilizer straps; this ensures nothing falls out!  I also appreciate that the grab handle is closer to the back of the pack instead of the top so it doesn't interfere with the zippers.  The only feature I would add to make it better is a luggage handle pass through strap. This is a replacement for the Osprey Nova that I used daily for almost 10 years.
review.name: The Perfect Backpack for Me!

review.reviewBody: Had various backpacks from Osprey, Deuter, Gregory and others along the road. The Nebula answered almost all my wishlist regarding other bags. The compretion straps keeps it small when it's relatively empty for day to day, but allow a very generous amount of gear when fully loaded. Great arrangement of pockets etc, and deep enough water bottle holders. Would love a little more serious waist belt, then it would really be perfect.
review.name: The best EDC / Travel backpack I owned

review.reviewBody: I really like the Nebula 32... it's got all the pockets you need and is great size for the office or a weekend trip. However, I don't understand the thought behind the shoulder straps... there is stark white foam that shows brightly through the blue (in my case) mesh that goes up and down the strap. Unfortunately, I can't help but feel like this was a design oversight. I see the white foam out of the corner of my eyes every time I turn my head... it's not a good look. To me, it looks cheap. Your mileage may vary. There is also a large piece of white foam on the rear of the pack to support a person's back... still not great, but it's at least hidden while wearing the backpack. In my case, the white foam is too distracting and I'm returning the bag. I'm bummed. Sorry, Osprey. :(
review.name: Great pack except...

review.reviewBody:
Yes i bought the best.  Yes i didnt have to.  Yes i bunny hop my road bike and push the limits.  But, its California and for some reason LA roads are crap.  At any moment its full brake or full gas and over the obstacle. 

Why- 
Here is why.  Im 5 11’ 194 - 187lbs normally.  Heavier side of a roady for sure. I have used now Time (lasted a month. Yes i know i max out their weight rating) I have used Look keo max carbon and lasted 4 month before coming dangerously loose.  So i went with the beefiest and nicest pedals i can find.  

Results. 
Non stop full gas fun.  I have literally just given these pedals my all.  Never EVER have i been more impressed and more in love.  Smooth, silky, butter me up and add sprinkles cause i cant get enough.   

PS i run all SRAM but my Shimano pedals and i dont care at all.  They are truly the best you can buy for durability. 

PSS the cleats are WAY better for me to walk around in.  Much more confidence off the bike even if those moments are short
review.name: Why not?

review.reviewBody:
I got these for an upcoming Gravel Race, and have been training on them and testing shoes.  Now most would choose an MTB style pedal for Gravel riding, and I agree that is usually the right choice.  But: one can save significant weight between road shoes and pedals, and the power transfer and feeling of all your power going into the bike with road pedals is fantastic.  For this race I know I will not need to unclip anywhere, so the road set up is appropriate.
What is there to say about the Dura Ace pedals?  They are perfect, low stack height, low profile, lightweight, easy to clip into, adjustable tension works well, and the bearing system in Dura Ace is fantastic-I suspect even the smooth bearings of these are an advantage over many other pedals.  Of course for Gravel the carbon/plastic body might get a little beat up, but they are road pedals and that is my choice, not Shimano's!
I do wish we would see so more interesting choices in pedals and shoes for Gravel racing, so far the perfect set up does not exist, and I switch back and forth between the lighter MTB shoes and the single sided PD-ES600 pedals and the road set up, depending on the course and conditions.
review.name: Dura Ace Pedal Review: Basically Perfect

name: Dura-Ace PD-R9100 SPD SL Pedals

review.reviewBody:
I decided to get this after an annoying buggy weekend. It’s not perfect but it gets the job done. 

Pros: Easy to set up with 2 people. All the posts are already connected so all you have to do is pull until they snap into place. It’s very roomy and can accommodate a camping table a few chairs and a dog. 

Cons: The blue fabric isn’t flush with the ground, though the grey does help cover. 

Recommendation: Since there is no floor you might want to put down a tarp before setting this up. It will help keep the shelter clean.  

We might look for a tarp to add to the outside for additional shade/privacy.
review.name: Good for what we need

Was going to get a new crankset anyways because I wanted a longer one, but didn't think carbon was going to fit in the budget. The GX carbon crank was an incredible value and works perfectly with other SRAM components. 

My only issue is this product did not come with the crank boots as shown. It's a really little thing, but I feel the manufacturer should have just included it. Now I'll have to place another order for something that's just a few bucks.

review.itemreviewed: GX Eagle DUB Carbon Crankset - Boost
review.reviewBody: When the new GX carbon cranks debuted, I initially thought it was a great idea.  This is a nice option for a sub-$300 crank with the stiffness of carbon.  Being a big hard-charging rider (who needs to get in the habit of spinning more and mashing less), I do notice and prefer the feel of carbon cranks.  With GX now having this option, I think the drivetrain group has become more compelling though I'd suggest combining it with a X01 shifter which has a nicer firmness to it.
review.name: Great Value in a Carbon Crankset

review.reviewBody: After spending a year of reading reviews and looking to upgrade, it was worth the price! I have a 2020 SB100 and it’s been a phenomenal bike. It’s still rides great! I only upgraded to handle some of the more technical trails Las Vegas has to offer! The SB 140 design clearly lives up to the reviews. review.itemreviewed: SB140 CLR GX Eagle AXS Factory 29in Mountain Bike
review.reviewBody: This bike is a serious Swiss army knife!  As someone who focuses on downhill performance, I was a bit timid to take a step down from my old 170mil rig, but with more pedaling in my life and fewer lifts and shuttles, I knew it needed to be done.  Needless to say, this bike has blown the doors off all my expectations, it is extremely capable on every trail I've ridden, Park City, UT is the home base for rides, and I have yet to feel underbiked or left wishing I had my longer travel bike.  Granted I have never ridden an XC or short travel bike, but I find that this bike pedals remarkably well, between the switch infinity and lockout on the shock, there is very little pedal bob and you are kept in great pedal postion.  I'd recommend this bike to anyone who is looking for a bike that one bike that can do it all.  Throw a coil on it and it'll really shine!
review.name: Quiver Killer!!!!

review.reviewBody: Great shoe!  Great fit, I have a wide forefoot and I have plenty of room to spread my toes out.  A little loose in the heel, but if you tie your shoes with a heel lock, keeps them nice and snug.  May take a few runs to get used to the higher stack height, I run in a pair of Hoka Cliftons as well and it took me 3-4 runs to get used to the difference.  Great cushioning gives it a plush ride.  I usually size up, but these were true to size.
review.name: On Cloudmonster 2

review.reviewBody: These shoes have a great bounce to them. Great for running and also have a great look. I wear mens size 10 typically, and these fit true to size. Recommend these
review.name: Mens Size 10 - mineral aloe color

review.reviewBody:
These are great, and super lightweight and comfortable out of the box! I've added my review here as these are the same for men or women :) (the sizing is based on the gender on the title). They even performed great on the trail. Also that white and orange color scheme looks absolutely fire, and I love the polka dotted shoelaces!
I'm not usually into maximally cushioned shoes, but I honestly really liked these. They are super light, but have tons of support too as another Gearhead mentioned - a nice stiff sole with a cushy footbed. They were even supportive enough for my feet and ankles to hit the trail. Not rock plate needed with that thick cushioned, protective sole! On Cloud has extensive tech in their air light sole - they are known as a top designer in this space for a reason and where they get the name from! The cubed sole you'll see on nearly all of their shoes is made of a special firm EVA (On Cloud calls it the Zero Gravity foam) with an open air pocket in the middle of the midsole and hollowed out cubes that are cut down the line of the shoe, which adds flexibility than most typical shoe soles.

For my couple hour run, I encountered some snow and mud and rocks. My feet never got too hot. These Monsters ventilate and breathe super well, which is important for me. They are also very responsive, so I was able to be precise on the trail. Also great for just strolling around the neighborhood. Did I mention how fire they look? I mean, just check out the pics! Also run true to size for my size 10 foot.
review.name: Awesome Sneaker with a Ton of Tech!

review.reviewBody:
The experience of walking in the Cloudmonster can be compared to having cylindrical rubber pieces horizontally affixed to your shoe soles, effortlessly compressing with each step. This was precisely the vision On's founders aimed for when crafting their inaugural shoe design.

Typically a trail runner, I've ventured onto the sidewalks with my new Cloudmonsters and couldn't be happier. Usually wearing a size 10 with most Hokas like the Speedgoat and Challenger, I opted for a 9.5 with these, and they fit perfectly. While I expected them to feel ultra-soft right out of the box, I was pleasantly surprised that after an hour-long jog, they maintained their firmness and springiness – a rare find in such heavily cushioned shoes. Overall, I believe these are an excellent choice for daily wear.
review.name: Daily Drivers!

review.reviewBody:
Right out of the box this shoe felt amazing in terms of fit and cushion. I normally wear 11.5 and this shoe fit fantastic. The toe box is on the wider side in my opinion. The upper was a super breathable and comfy material. One issue I ran into though is with the wider toe box and upper material, it is a little difficult to really lock down those lower laces. I was able to look past this issue though, but feel like should be noted for anyone with narrower feet. I was also a big fan of the rockered geometry of the shoe. It really wants you to move forward and get up on the midfoot/toes. 

#BackcountryGearhead
review.name: Love for a great cushioned Monster.

review.reviewBody: I had the original Cloudmonster and loved them. For anything from long runs to speed work, these shoes have held up well. Moving on to the second iteration, the Cloudmonster 2's, I was happy to see they added even MORE cushioning. I love max cushioned shoes for my long runs. I'm a heavier-than-average runner, so the cushioning really helps with ankle and knee fatigue during long runs. The rocker profile helps with speedier transitions as well. The fit of the shoe is very similar to the original, though I think it's slightly roomier both in overall length and width. I wear a size 11.5 across the board and that's what I ordered here. I've only done a few runs in them so far so I'll have to come back and comment on the durability, but if they hold up as well as the originals, I'll be wearing them a long time!
review.name: Amazing Comfort for Long Miles

review.reviewBody:
LOVE this jacket!  I'm 6'2 and bought XL for extra movement and layering when snowboarding. 
Pros: The synthetic fill is the best I've ever felt, I honestly thought it was down fill.  
I love that it stays warm and holds its lofty puffiness when in wet snow conditions. 
My other Sitka down jacket loses its loft quickly in the arms and back when I start perspiring from a morning of hiking or snowboarding. 
But's it's so soft a cozy.  I often just wear a t-shirt or thin base layer under it if I'm just staring around a camp fire. 
It's very warm and the hand and chin backings are super soft. 

Cons: My only complaint is that it doesn't have a well placed hood draw string for windy conditions.  The single draw string on the hood is more a retention string for side to side movement of your head.  
And the outer fabric is very delicate, I know its gonna snag and tear on a tree branch one of these days....I personally wish it was a little bit thicker like on my wife's Expedition down jacket.

review.reviewBody: It's a great jacket for cold, wet winters. The fact that it is not down makes it more resistant to rain but no less warm. review.reviewBody: I bought this backpack a year ago and really wanted to put it through the test before I wrote a review. I took my Mira 22 on a week long trip of all day hiking adventures. I had plenty of room for lunch, clothing and other items I may have needed. I really liked the magnetic clip for the hydration mouth piece and had no problems with it. My iPhone 14 Pro did fit in a hip belt pocket as I had a thin cover but it would be great if the hip belt pockets were slightly longer. I really liked the ventilation in the back and how the pack fit my back. I am 5' 0" tall. One of the best features is the attached rain cover which came in handy. I wish all backpacks came with attached rain covers. I was amazed at how much one could carry in this backpack. I highly recommend the Mira 22.
review.name: Awesome, Comfortable Backpack for Day Hiking!

review.reviewBody: I bought this backpack a year ago and half ago. I finally got to put it to a true test this fall traveling overseas and day hiking in varied weather. I am short, 5', and this backpack fit me perfectly as it is women's specific. I like that it has a rain cover attached to it as hiking in high winds if it comes off it is attached to the pack and does not fly away. Love the water bladder east to fill, connect, and had plenty of water for day hiking in middle of September. Plenty of room for extra gloves, hats, rain gear, shirts, and seat pad, lunch and snacks. I also attached a pair of water shoes as I was crossing rivers. My iPhone pro does fit in one of the side pockets. It would be nice if the side pocket could be a touch longer for today's style of phones. I like that it has the airspeed suspension and really helps with ventilation. Also, I used the Mira 22 as a carry on on the plane and I could put most of it under the seat. I highly recommend the Mira 22 for day hikes.
review.name: Excellent Day Hiking Backpack, Rain Cover Attached

review.reviewBody: This pack has been perfect for my longer hikes. I am a slow hiker so need more nutrition and water. I recently went on a 16 mile hike with 4500 feet elevation change. I took it at an easy pace for me and it took me 15 hours. I actually attached two bladders inside the bladder compartment so I could bring 4 L of water. This pack worked very nicely for me for this hike, and the other longer hikes I went on to prepare for this.
review.name: Love it!

name: Mira 22L Hydration Backpack - Women's

review.itemreviewed: Challenger Mid GTX Hiking Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I have heel spurs. My doctor has recommended for the time being to hold off on surgery to remove, as he said it will be a painful and extensive recovery. Ouch! So I have to deal with them and with the wrong shoes, it was becoming increasingly difficult to do so and becoming more and more painful. I had to give up my trail walks, which literally broke my heart & spirit. I bought countless types and brands of shoes, tried every insert out there, all to no avail. Then someone online recommended the HOKA brand to me. I chose this shoe to see if I could back out on the trails with them. As soon as I put them on, I knew they were different! And they were! ZERO pain when walking! ZERO pain after walking, as was usually the case. ZERO pain the next day! I am BEYOND thrilled!! Thank you so very much for creating such a wonderful brand. Now to pick out my next pair... :)
review.name: Best Shoe EVER!

review.itemreviewed: Challenger Mid GTX Hiking Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought these boots, because they were recommended by the American Podiatric Medical Association. I love to hike with my husband and our dog, but I have foot problems that limit my hiking trips. Well, my Hoka Challenger Mid Gore-Tex boots have changed that! They're super supportive and comfy, and they have all the qualities needed in a good hiking boot - they're waterproof, warm, and able to tackle a variety of terrains. They also look good. Who'd have thought a shoe designed to support your feet could also look stylish and youthful - not like old school orthopedic shoes/boots. I love 'em! If you need a great pair of hiking boots - get a pair of these Hoka's!!
review.name: I would buy this product again, and recommend it to a friend

review.itemreviewed: Challenger Mid GTX Hiking Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: First the good: so comfortable right out of the box. Well-cushioned. Warm and waterproof. But the lacing system! I guess I have forever taken lacing systems for granted since they are a forgettable but necessary part of most any shoe. Not this one. First to get the shoe on you have to loosen up each lace individually to get your foot in. Then to tighten you need to retrace your steps and tighten each loop individually. Then you need to position the flat lace at the right angle to engage the top two loops. I'm imagining this design was to keep the laces from loosening during wear, but trust me, these suckers aren't loosening without some serious effort on your part. I have a pair of Hoka running shoes that lace up with eases, so I'm not sure what the philosophy was here, but they're lucky this boot is so comfortable or I'd never put up with the hassle of getting them on and off.
review.name: Amazing comfort, brutal lacing system

review.itemreviewed: Challenger Mid GTX Hiking Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I love the ankle support and how my feet didn't slide into the end of the shoe. Great stability! The only thing I wished for was a more plush insole and a little more narrow. I love Hokas and have many people buying them due to their issues with their feet.
review.name: I was impressed!

review.reviewBody: I went back and forth on spending this much money on a child trailer for about 7 months. I talked myself out of it multiple times. My son hit 18 months and is incredibly active, hates being cooped up inside, and I needed some exercise so I finally pulled the trigger and I’m glad I did. I’m impressed with build quality, safety, and stability. I can’t even tell I’m pulling anything, it corners so well and is so quiet I often turn around to make sure he is still there! Easy setup. Easy install. Very happy with this purchase, should last a lifetime. If you’re on the fence, go for it.

review.reviewBody: We bought this Thule Lite Chariot from our local bike shop and have has it for a few years now. We bought it when our 2nd kid was a baby and now we have 4 kids that have all used this Chariot A TON and it is still going strong with more years of use still to come! Our only regret is not buying this sooner... seriously, the bike adventures we have been able to take our little kids on now because of this have been worth every penny this Chariot cost us. We have also purchased the Jogging Kit for this Chariot, and use this as a stroller in heavy duty snowy conditions and for running (sometimes running in heavy duty snowy conditions!) and it's served us soooo well. Zero complaints. We have the infant sling to use when our babies are young, and when they are older, we love that this is such an easy stroller for kids to hop in and out of themselves when we are at the zoo or some other activity they want to be in and out lots for. We have used it for 2 kids or 1 kid and a dog or just 1 kid on their own with extra room for backpacks and coats for school drop off and pickup. Wouldn't recommend this enough... literally has changed our life and how much fun we can have with our kids!!!
review.name: Excellent bike trailer AND stroller

review.reviewBody: We love love love our Thule Chariot. Our kids love riding in it with their dad on the bike! We are waiting for the jogging kit 2 to be available again so i can take them running. We love Thule products!

review.reviewBody:
Love it! Best stroller for our family with two
Kids.

review.reviewBody:
I purchased the Chariot Lite double about a month ago and I've been very satisfied with it. Previous to owning the Chariot Lite I had a Chariot Cross, which I loved as well but it was unfortunately stolen. When replacing it I opted for the slightly cheaper slightly lighter Chariot Lite and I think I like it even more than the Cross. The dimensions and utility of the two are the same, the notable differences being the Cross has a retractable trunk, reclining seats and the suspension is adjustable. I almost never adjusted the seats or suspension in the 4 years we owned the Cross and while I liked the retractable trunk, I decided that I'd be ok settling for the mesh pocket on the Lite. 
Having used the Chariot Lite for several weeks I can say I think I prefer the mesh pocket over the trunk and I've appreciated the 4lb reduction in weight when listing it up stairs or into the back of our car.
Both the Lite and the Cross are the same dimensions, which on the double, is quite wide, barely fitting through standard doorways. Although I only have 1 child, I'm glad I have the extra width for carrying groceries, a kids bike, one of our kid's friends, etc.
One last note: We did bring the Chariot Cross on an airplane earlier this year before we had to replace it, and while it got a few strange looks from airline staff at first, we got several compliments on how flat it folded down with the wheels off, and they checked it as a stroller without issue.
review.name: Excellent, more than enough features

review.reviewBody: The Thule Chariot Lite has been great. Our 2 year old things it's comfortable, at least comfortable enough to sleep in a few time, and it's incredibly easy to use. Being able to switch from pulling behind the bike to pushing as a stroller in seconds has come in handy a few times.
review.name: Easy to use and sturdy

review.reviewBody: The Rux is a great tote that lives in my truck.  I keep all my essential outdoor gear in it so I'm always ready to roll and never forget any of my gear.  I can easily move it when needed and it carries weight extremely well. Plus its waterproof and cleans up well so if I have muddy shoes or wet skins after skiing, I don't have to worry about getting the rest of my truck dirty.  The few times I've taken it out of my truck, it packs up small so it doesn't take up a lot of space when not in use.
review.name: The ultimate storage solution

review.reviewBody: I absolutely love my Rux. I wasn't sure how much and for what activities I'd use it for, but turns out I can't leave the house without. Whether I'm going skiing (so easy to toss pack, boots, helmet, layers in the Rux instead of making trips and forgetting things), biking (helmet, shoes, knee pads, beer), freediving, surfing, etc... it's perfect for making my life an organized burrito instead of a loose taco salad of gear in my truck. It cleans super easy and the divider keeps wet or muddy things well away from my precious clean and dry things.
review.name: Rux changed everything.

review.reviewBody:
If you are like me and practice multiple sports year round, you need this.

I've been using my RUX before and after every single snowboard day this winter to pack and unpack, and now it comes with me on every Climbing & Camping occasion.

I would never use any other alternative for gear storage.

Very convenient, super durable and easy to clean. Likely to buy again to get better organisation in my gear.
review.name: Outdoor gear management necessity

review.reviewBody: My RUX has become my go to for pretty much every outing. If I could have half a dozen of them I would. I thought it might be overkill, but it is just really handy. I can fit all my ski gear in one for a day, moto gear, climbing rack, a picnic with the family. I even checked it on a flight once. Super useful.
review.name: More useful than I even realized

review.reviewBody: The RUX 70L has truly upped my game when it comes to organizing for a trip. With a baby in tow, our camping and roadtripping logistics have become a lot more complicated. From stowing our camp kitchen essentials, to lugging firewood, to giving the lil' guy a bath, the RUX 70L is a camping necessity.
review.name: Game Changing gear organization

review.reviewBody: The RUX has been my sidekick since I purchased it! Love the look and feel of it not to mention the great customer service the brand has AND the life time warranty makes the price well worth it.
review.name: Could not be happier!

review.reviewBody: love how consistently we get use out of our RUX. EVERY weekend, plus here n there in between. more than I can say about any other duffel or container we have. lake, skiing, beaches, road trips, family weekends (which is evry weekend). getting a tonne of use and going to keep on doing so.
review.name: winter or summer, all in

review.reviewBody: Hello, I recently purchased the trailer kit, however, it doesn't seem to be compatible with the Thule Chariot Sport Double. The bicycle trailer kit arm is square and the opening on my chariot sport seems to be more of a triangle. Is there another kit or suggestion for the Chariot Sport Double?
review.name: Trouble installing on my Thule Chariot Sport

review.reviewBody: Bought this to use with our Cougar 2. Very easy to put together and works great. Easy to take on and off and stores nicely on the side of the carrier. Directions were easy to follow.
review.name: Works great with Cougar 2

review.reviewBody: All of us love this. Happy toddler, happy parents. Feels very secure and well made too. Highly recommend!
review.name: So worth it

review.reviewBody: Got A used 9001 trunk carrier and was missing a bottom hook. Thule made it so easy to make it a complete unit. It is a great bike rack.
review.name: Thule is awesome!

review.reviewBody: I love my Thule cheetah chariot and I am happy I purchased the trailer kit. It works wonderfully and I have a blast towing my baby around on bike rides. However, when I received the item the directions were written for a different model of chariot so there were a few things I had to do differently then what the directions said and it was confusing at times and it was hard to follow. I figured it out eventually though and now it is very easy to detach and re attach the trailer kit.
review.name: Satisfied with the product, directions hard to follow

review.reviewBody:
We bought this for going on walks, bike rides and snowshoeing adventures. 
It is very manouverable and packable. 
Switching between the stroller and bike setup is incredibly easy.
The harnesses are comfortable and easy to use. The storage pocket in the back is well worth it.

The only improvement I would recommend is the front cover connection. When the cover is correctly aligned over the frame it latches, but otherwise it can slip off. It hasn't been a problem for our use, but it is an area where things could be improved.

Overall this is the best, most versatile stroller on the market. The attachments are well worth it.
review.name: Unparalleled quality
